Data Visualisation POC: Waarneming.nl

The library that I used for this POC is kepler, you can make your own visualisations quite easily at https://kepler.gl/demo provided you know a little bit about html, css, javascript and react it’s not difficult to add an explanation to your visualisation.

To prepare for this visualization I’ve answered a few questions:

  Exploratory or explanatory?

This visualisation should be more exploratory than explanatory because researchers and schools should be able to come to their own conclusions from the data, the data will give insight not one answer. The reason it’s still a bit explanatory is because it is about biodiversity and you should be able to compare different places in the netherlands. So in this visualisation we’re around the middle but more towards exploratory.

  Who’s the target audience?

The target audience for this visualisation are not experts but people with some domain knowledge, people that won’t believe everything they see and want to explore. Not the general audience.

  What kind of charts do you need?

An interactive map with catching visuals.

  What kind of data is available?

I’ve used the dataset from waarneming.nl itself because this visualisation is for the project.

  How large is the dataset?

The dataset is very large, we start with 28.8million observations and could add more observations from different open source datasets if we’d like.







Biodiversity in the Netherlands

In this data visualisation biodiversity in the netherlands is quantified by number of different species in an area. This definition of biodiversity will be refined over the course of the project.
